  "prompt_type": "cognitive",
  "prompt_text": "A farmer has 100 meters of fencing and wants to enclose the largest possible rectangular area. What dimensions should the rectangle have?",
  "response_text": "To maximize the area enclosed by 100 meters of fencing for a rectangular plot, we need to consider the relationship between the length \\( L \\) and the width \\( W \\) of the rectangle.\n\nThe perimeter of the rectangle is given by:\n\\[ P = 2L + 2W \\]\n\nGiven that the total fencing available is 100 meters, we can set up the equation:\n\\[ 2L + 2W = 100 \\]\n\nSimplifying this equation, we get:\n\\[ L + W = 50 \\]\n\nOur goal is to maximize the area \\( A \\), which is given by:\n\\[ A = L \\times W \\]\n\nFrom the simplified perimeter equation, we can express \\( W \\) in terms of \\( L \\):\n\\[ W = 50 - L \\]\n\nSubstituting this into the area formula gives us:\n\\[ A = L \\times (50 - L) \\]\n\\[ A = 50L - L^2 \\]\n\nThis is a quadratic equation in the form \\( A = -L^2 + 50L \\). The graph of this parabola opens downwards, indicating that it has a maximum point.\n\nFor a quadratic function \\( ax^2 + bx + c \\), the vertex occurs at \\( x = -\\frac{b}{2a} \\). Here, \\( a = -1 \\) and \\( b = 50 \\), so:\n\\[ L = -\\frac{50}{2(-1)} \\]\n\\[ L = \\frac{50}{2} \\]\n\\[ L = 25 \\]\n\nThus, the dimensions that maximize the area are:\n\\[ L = 25 \\text{ meters} \\]\n\\[ W = 50 - 25 \\text{ meters} \\]\n\\[ W = 25 \\text{ meters} \\]\n\nTherefore, the dimensions of the rectangle that will enclose the largest possible area using 100 meters of fencing are:\n\\[ \\boxed{25 \\text{ meters by } 25 \\text{ meters}} \\]",
